## Theorem: mathd_numbertheory_466

Theorem: mathd_numbertheory_466
Prove: (∑ k in (finset.range 11), k) % 9 = 1

Goal: (∑ k in (finset.range 11), k) % 9 = 1

## English proof (from stage 1)
{
  "key_observation": "The sum of the first 11 natural numbers is 55, and 55 leaves remainder 1 when divided by 9.",
  "plan": [
    "Evaluate the finite sum \\(\\sum_{k=0}^{10} k\\) using the standard arithmetic series formula.",
    "Reduce the resulting integer modulo 9.",
    "Conclude that the remainder is 1."
  ],
  "steps": [
    {
      "claim": "∑ k in (finset.range 11), k = 55.",
      "reasoning": "The set `finset.range 11` is the list of integers from 0 through 10. Their sum is an arithmetic series with 11 terms, so the sum is \\(11 \\cdot 10 / 2 = 55\\).",
      "facts_used": [
        "sum_range",
        "arithmetic series formula"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "(∑ k in (finset.range 11), k) % 9 = 55 % 9.",
      "reasoning": "By step 1, the sum is exactly 55, so replacing the sum by 55 preserves the value of the expression modulo 9.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 1",
        "congruence respects equality"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "55 % 9 = 1.",
      "reasoning": "Since 55 = 9 · 6 + 1, the remainder upon division by 9 is 1.",
      "facts_used": [
        "division algorithm",
        "definition of modulo"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "(∑ k in (finset.range 11), k) % 9 = 1.",
      "reasoning": "Combining steps 2 and 3 gives the desired result.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 2",
        "step 3"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "final_answer": "1"
}

